## Section 6: Inter-Agent Communication & Dynamic Team Composition

**This is the core differentiator — agents autonomously composing teams at runtime.**

### 6.1 Communication Model

Agents communicate through the daemon's message bus using a **mailbox pattern**. Each agent has an inbox (receives) and can send to any agent within its namespace.

```
                    ┌─────────────────────┐
                    │    Daemon Bus        │
                    │                     │
                    │  ┌───────────────┐  │
          ┌────────►│  │ Router        │  │◄────────┐
          │         │  │  - namespace  │  │         │
          │         │  │  - ACL check  │  │         │
          │         │  │  - dead letter│  │         │
          │         │  └───────────────┘  │         │
          │         └─────────────────────┘         │
          │              │           │              │
    ┌─────┴─────┐  ┌─────┴─────┐  ┌─────┴─────┐
    │ Agent A   │  │ Agent B   │  │ Agent C   │
    │ inbox: 📬 │  │ inbox: 📬 │  │ inbox: 📬 │
    │ outbox: 📤│  │ outbox: 📤│  │ outbox: 📤│
    └───────────┘  └───────────┘  └───────────┘
```

**Three communication primitives:**

```rust
// 1. Request/Reply — synchronous (from agent's perspective)
//    Agent A asks Agent B a question and blocks until response
let response = bus.request(
    to: AgentId("agent-b"),
    payload: json!({ "type": "review", "file": "src/main.rs", "diff": "..." }),
    timeout: Duration::from_secs(120),
).await?;

// 2. Fire-and-forget — async notification
//    Agent A tells siblings about something, doesn't wait
bus.send(
    to: AgentId("agent-b"),
    payload: json!({ "type": "file_changed", "path": "src/lib.rs" }),
).await?;

// 3. Broadcast — pub/sub within namespace
//    Agent A announces to all siblings + parent
bus.broadcast(
    topic: "progress",
    payload: json!({ "phase": "testing", "percent": 75 }),
).await?;
```

### 6.2 Dynamic Team Composition

**The primary agent gets a `spawn` tool exposed via its MCP socket.** This is how it autonomously builds teams:

```json
// Tools available to the primary agent via MCP
{
  "tools": [
    {
      "name": "forge_spawn_agent",
      "description": "Spawn a sub-agent with a specific profile and task",
      "input_schema": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "profile": { "type": "string", "description": "Nix agent profile name" },
          "task": { "type": "string", "description": "What this agent should do" },
          "wait": { "type": "boolean", "description": "Block until agent completes" }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "forge_message_agent",
      "description": "Send a message to another agent and optionally wait for reply",
      "input_schema": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "agent_id": { "type": "string" },
          "payload": { "type": "object" },
          "wait_reply": { "type": "boolean" },
          "timeout_secs": { "type": "integer" }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "forge_list_agents",
      "description": "List all agents in your namespace with their status"
    },
    {
      "name": "forge_kill_agent",
      "description": "Terminate a child agent",
      "input_schema": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "agent_id": { "type": "string" },
          "reason": { "type": "string" }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Example: Primary agent dynamically composes a team:**

```
Primary Agent (profile: "orchestrator")
│
│ [Reads spec, decides it needs 3 parallel implementers + 1 reviewer]
│
├── forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Implement auth module")
│   → Agent A spawned (auto-approved, within soft cap)
│
├── forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Implement API routes")
│   → Agent B spawned (auto-approved)
│
├── forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Implement database layer")
│   → Agent C spawned (auto-approved)
│
├── forge_spawn_agent(profile: "security-reviewer", task: "Review all changes when implementers complete")
│   → Agent D spawned (auto-approved)
│
│ [Agents A, B, C work in parallel on shared workspace]
│
│ Agent A completes → broadcasts("progress", { "module": "auth", "status": "done" })
│ Agent B completes → broadcasts("progress", { "module": "api", "status": "done" })
│ Agent C has a question → request(to: Agent A, { "type": "question", "about": "auth token format" })
│   Agent A replies → { "format": "JWT", "schema": "..." }
│ Agent C completes
│
│ [Primary sees all 3 done via broadcast, messages reviewer]
│
├── forge_message_agent(agent_id: D, payload: { "type": "start_review" }, wait_reply: true)
│   → Agent D reviews all changes, replies with findings
│
│ [Primary reads findings, decides Agent C's work needs fixes]
│
├── forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Fix issues in database layer: ...")
│   → Agent E spawned (5th agent — still under soft cap)
│
├── forge_spawn_agent(profile: "implementer", task: "Add integration tests")
│   → Agent F — 6th agent, exceeds require-approval-after=5
│   → APPROVAL GATE: daemon sends ApprovalRequest to Primary
│   → Primary approves (via forge_approve_spawn tool)
│   → Agent F spawned
